Question 1: What excites you to come to work every day?
What excites me most is being able to apply my cross-functional expertise in both modelling and auditing I have built over many years directly to protecting the bank.
As a model auditor, I review and challenge the models the bank relies on, from marketing and fraud models to other models that inform business decisions. What I find most meaningful is using my judgment to identify flaws, uncover underestimated risks, and address issues before they lead to real losses.
At its core, my role is about helping ensure the right models support the right decisions and reducing avoidable risk to the bank. That is work with real impact, and that is what motivates me every day.
Question 2: What does not excite you, or what frustrates you?
What frustrates me most is when model audit is treated as a documentation exercise rather than a true assessment of risk and impact.
Models do not operate in isolation. They influence business decisions and can create downstream consequences for the bank. That is where the real risk often sits.
In practice, though, reviews can stop at the model documentation. When I try to assess the downstream impact of a finding, there can be pushback due to limited information or pressure to stay on schedule. That is frustrating, because a finding that is identified but not evaluated for its broader impact is only a partial audit.
Some issues may appear minor on the surface but carry meaningful consequences downstream. I do my best work when I have the ability to follow the risk to where it actually matters, not just to where the checklist ends.







Question: What is one thing I could do as your leader that would help you do your best work or feel more included?
The one thing that would make the greatest difference is this: help me navigate the dynamics and back me when it counts.
As a model auditor, the quality of my conclusions depends on having complete context. At times, I may identify a deficiency without visibility into related regulatory discussions, remediation plans, or leadership decisions already underway. When that context is missing, it can affect the accuracy and fairness of the audit.
What would help most is, first, helping me better understand how the teams connect, where decisions are made, and where important context may sit. Second, when I need to ask for information that is not readily shared or when a valid finding faces resistance, your support would make a real difference.
With that context and support, I can do stronger audit work that is accurate, fair, and more useful to the bank.


Question 4: what makes you feel recognized and/or support? 
The most powerful form of recognition for me does not come from verbal praise. It comes from seeing my work create real impact, when I raise a significant model risk, it is taken seriously, followed up on, and acted upon. That is the moment I feel my contribution has genuinely been seen.
What also matters is having my professional judgment carry the right weight. I spend a lot of time assessing model assumptions, data, and outputs, so it is meaningful when well-supported findings, especially difficult ones, are not softened or set aside.
Finally, I feel most supported when I know I will have backing in challenging situations. Audit work often involves raising issues that others may not want to hear. When a well-grounded finding faces pushback, leadership support makes a real difference.
In the end, I feel most recognized and supported when I can focus on the risks that matter most and know that sound judgment will be taken seriously.




#5: what else should I know about the team, the current culture, what is working what is not working.
What is working:
The team is technically strong, hardworking, and accountable. People take ownership of their work and are committed to delivering on time. That discipline is a real strength.
What needs to improve:
The team needs to move beyond a task-completion mindset and focus more on risk and impact. That shift is cultural and needs to be led from the top.
